│ the `ir-bb<loop.preheader>` block. The value `%step` is the result of an `invoke`          │
│ instruction, which is defined outside the loop.\n3.  The vectorizer decides on a           │
│ vectorization factor (VF) of 4 and an unroll/interleave factor (UF) of 2.\n4.  The final   │
│ VPlan is generated and execution begins.\n5.  The log shows `LV: vectorizing               │
│ VPBB:ir-bb<loop.preheader> in BB:loop.preheader` and `LV: vectorizing                      │
│ VPBB:ir-bb<vector.ph> in BB:vector.ph`, and then it crashes.\n\nThe crash occurs while     │
│ processing the `vector.ph` block of the VPlan. The backtrace points to                     │
│ `VPTransformState::get`, which is called while generating code for a                       │
│ `VPInstruction`.\n\n### Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how the     │
│ loop vectorizer handles the value `%step`, which is computed by an `invoke`                │
│ instruction.\n\n1.  **SCEV Expansion of `invoke`:** The loop vectorizer represents         │
│ loop-invariant values using SCEV (Scalar Evolution). For `%step`, it creates a SCEV        │
│ expression. To make the value available in the vectorized code, it uses a `SCEVExpander`   │
│ to generate IR instructions that compute the value. The `EXPAND SCEV %step` recipe in the  │
│ VPlan represents this operation.\n\n2.  **`SCEVExpander` and `invoke`:** The               │
│ `SCEVExpander` is designed to insert code at a specific insertion point. When expanding    │
│ the SCEV for `%step`, it finds that `%step` is defined by an `invoke` instruction (`I`).   │
│ The expander's logic then attempts to clone the `invoke` instruction.\n\n3.  **Incorrect   │
│ Insertion Point:** The `SCEVExpander` is configured with an insertion point (`InsertPt`)   │
│ which, in this case, is the terminator of the `entry` block (the original `invoke`         │
│ instruction). The `IRBuilder` used by the expander inserts new instructions *before* the   │
│ `InsertPt`. When `SCEVExpander` decides to clone the `invoke` instruction, it tries to     │
│ insert the clone into a block that already has a terminator. This is illegal and results   │
│ in an instruction that is not properly linked into any basic block.\n\n4.  **The Crash:**  │
│ The cloned instruction, now disconnected from any basic block, is returned by the          │
│ expander. Later, the vectorizer's `VPTransformState::get` function receives this           │
│ instruction. When it tries to operate on it (e.g., by getting its parent basic block), it  │
│ accesses invalid data because the instruction is not in a basic block's instruction list.  │
│ This leads to the `!NodePtr->isKnownSentinel()` assertion when trying to dereference an    │
│ iterator that is effectively pointing to a list sentinel.\n\nThe fundamental bug is that   │
│ `SCEVExpander` does not correctly handle the case where it needs to expand a value defined │
│ by a terminator instruction like `invoke`. It should not clone the terminator. Instead, it │
│ should use the original value, provided it dominates the insertion point.\n\n### Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to modify `SCEVExpander::visitUnknown` to handle this case.    │
│ Before attempting to clone the instruction `I`, we check if the insertion point is a       │
│ terminator. If it is, and it's in the same basic block as the instruction to be cloned, we │
│ should adjust the insertion point to be the terminator itself. This will cause the         │
│ subsequent `isAvailableAt` check to succeed, preventing the illegal clone.\n\n```diff\n--- │
│ a/llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp\n+++                                       │
│ b/llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolutionExpander.cpp\n@@ -1098,6 +1098,9 @@\n   // If this is a │
│ loop-invariant value, we must be inserting the code in the\n   // loop preheader.\n   if   │
│ (I) {\n+    if (auto *T = dyn_cast<TerminatorInst>(InsertPt))\n+      if (T->getParent()   │
│ == I->getParent())\n+        InsertPt = T;\n     // If we have a DominatorTree, verify     │
│ that the inserted value will\n     // dominate the insert point. If we don't have a        │
│ DominatorTree, we can't\n     // do this check.\n\n```\n\nThis change checks if the        │
│ insertion point `InsertPt` is a terminator instruction `T`. If it is, and if the           │
│ instruction `I` we are considering expanding is in the same basic block as `T`, we update  │
│ `InsertPt` to be `T`. This ensures that when `isAvailableAt(I, InsertPt)` is called        │
│ shortly after, it will correctly determine that `I` is available at `InsertPt` (since an   │
│ instruction is available at its own location), preventing the illegal clone                │
│ attempt.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe crash was caused by `SCEVExpander` illegally cloning a   │
│ terminator instruction (`invoke`) because the insertion point was set to that same         │
│ terminator. The proposed fix adjusts the logic to recognize this situation and avoid the   │
│ clone, instead correctly identifying that the original value is already available. This    │
│ ensures the generated IR is valid and resolves the crash."})                               │
